clean_text:
- Differentiate among a floating exchange rate, a soft peg, a hard peg, and a merged currency
- Identify the tradeoffs that come with a floating exchange rate, a soft peg, a hard peg, and a merged currency


Exchange rate policies come in a range of different forms listed in Figure 17.9:
<Image
  alt="The graph shows several options of exchange rate policies."
  src="/images/module-5/chapter-17/section-4/5b492d412edb7a86c51fdbefe72f34e4d9989d7c.png"
  width={700}
  height={400}

Figure 17.9 A Spectrum of Exchange Rate Policies




Floating exchange rate: Let the foreign exchange market determine the exchange rate;


Soft peg: Let the market set the value of the exchange rate most of the time, but have the central bank sometimes intervene to prevent fluctuations that seem too large;


Hard peg: Have the central bank guarantee a specific exchange rate; or


Merged currency: Share a currency with other countries.

